WEBVTT

00:06.240 --> 00:08.000
["Whole Wide World"
by Wreckless Eric playing]

00:13.760 --> 00:16.920
♪ When I was a young boy ♪

00:18.040 --> 00:21.920
♪ My mama said to me ♪

00:21.960 --> 00:24.040
♪ There's only one girl ♪

00:24.080 --> 00:26.760
♪ In the world for you ♪

00:26.800 --> 00:30.920
♪ She probably lives in Tahiti ♪

00:30.960 --> 00:32.880
♪ I'd go the whole wide world ♪

00:32.920 --> 00:36.560
♪ I'd go the whole wide world
just to find her ♪

00:37.520 --> 00:39.560
[men shouting]

00:42.200 --> 00:46.280
♪ Well, maybe
she's in the Bahamas ♪

00:46.320 --> 00:50.760
♪ Where the Caribbean Sea
is blue ♪

00:50.800 --> 00:54.640
♪ Weeping in a tropical
moonlit night ♪

00:54.680 --> 00:58.520
♪ Because nobody's told
about you ♪

00:58.560 --> 01:01.560
♪ I'd go the whole wide world ♪

01:01.600 --> 01:05.680
♪ I'd go the whole wide world
just to find her ♪

01:05.720 --> 01:07.960
♪ I'd go the whole wide world ♪

01:08.000 --> 01:11.200
♪ I'd go the whole wide world
to find out ♪

01:11.240 --> 01:13.320
♪ Where they hide her ♪

01:13.360 --> 01:15.080
♪ I'd go the whole wide world ♪

01:15.120 --> 01:19.360
♪ I'd go the whole wide world
just to find her ♪

01:28.480 --> 01:30.840
♪ Why am I hanging around ♪

01:30.880 --> 01:33.720
♪ In the rain out here ♪

01:33.760 --> 01:37.240
♪ Trying to pick up a girl ♪

01:37.280 --> 01:39.440
♪ Why are my eyes filling up ♪

01:39.480 --> 01:41.800
♪ With these lonely tears ♪

01:41.840 --> 01:45.400
♪ When there's girls
all over the world ♪

01:45.440 --> 01:50.360
♪ Or is she lying on
a tropical beach somewhere ♪

01:50.400 --> 01:55.280
♪ Underneath the tropical sun ♪

01:55.320 --> 01:59.880
♪ Hiding away
in a heat wave there ♪

01:59.920 --> 02:02.720
♪ Hoping that I won't be long ♪

02:02.760 --> 02:04.760
♪ I should be lying ♪

02:04.800 --> 02:07.920
♪ On that sun-soaked beach
with her ♪

02:07.960 --> 02:11.880
♪ Caressing
her warm brown skin ♪

02:11.920 --> 02:14.120
♪ And then at the end
of the year ♪

02:14.160 --> 02:16.600
♪ Or maybe not quite ♪

02:16.640 --> 02:20.480
♪ We'll be sharing
the same next of kin ♪

02:20.520 --> 02:22.840
♪ I'd go the whole wide world ♪

02:22.880 --> 02:27.280
♪ I'd go the whole wide world
just to find her ♪

02:27.320 --> 02:28.840
♪ Yeah. ♪

02:43.400 --> 02:44.840
Jenny, there you are.

02:44.880 --> 02:46.360
JENNY [over phone]:
How is she doing?

02:46.400 --> 02:49.000
I don't know. [exhales]

02:49.040 --> 02:51.000
I'm not sure
what state she's in.

02:51.040 --> 02:53.680
She rang to say
she was ready to go home.

02:55.400 --> 02:57.640
She has to connect
through here in Kinshasa

02:57.680 --> 03:00.920
so when I pick her up, I guess
I'll find out a bit more.

03:00.960 --> 03:03.720
-JENNY: Just come home safe.
-Yeah, I will.

03:03.760 --> 03:05.720
Yeah. Bye.

03:13.520 --> 03:15.520
♪ ♪

03:30.600 --> 03:32.600
♪ ♪

03:50.960 --> 03:52.200
[car horn honks]

04:08.680 --> 04:10.160
Here.

04:15.640 --> 04:19.200
Was he always a liar
or am I just-just stupid?

04:21.080 --> 04:22.840
No, not stupid, just in love.

04:22.880 --> 04:25.960
I'm not sure
there's much of a difference.

04:26.000 --> 04:27.800
People change.

04:27.840 --> 04:30.120
Not as much
as I'd like to think.

04:30.160 --> 04:31.360
Right?

04:33.560 --> 04:36.680
At least you know the truth now.

04:36.720 --> 04:38.160
You know
the cowardly little shit

04:38.200 --> 04:39.720
has been holed up in Rwanda.

04:39.760 --> 04:42.360
Oh, maybe I was better off
not knowing.

04:42.400 --> 04:44.840
And live with the uncertainty?
I don't think so.

04:44.880 --> 04:48.360
It doesn't mean that the life
you had together wasn't real

04:48.400 --> 04:52.120
and it doesn't mean
that he didn't love you... once.

04:52.160 --> 04:54.200
But what he did is--

04:54.240 --> 04:56.320
makes all that irrelevant.

04:56.360 --> 04:57.680
I mean, it's--

04:57.720 --> 04:59.720
-All that time, just...
-Georgia. Georgia.

04:59.760 --> 05:02.440
-...wasted.
-Hey.

05:03.640 --> 05:04.920
Come on.

05:08.480 --> 05:11.200
[exhales]
Did you find Adidja?

05:11.240 --> 05:13.120
[sighs]

05:13.160 --> 05:15.440
No.

05:15.480 --> 05:17.440
-[exhales]
-I'm sorry.

05:22.960 --> 05:25.360
There must be something
we can do.

05:26.960 --> 05:28.880
I tried, Georgia,
I really tried.

05:28.920 --> 05:31.040
[phone ringing]

05:31.080 --> 05:34.400
And if you found her,
what would you do? Hmm?

05:34.440 --> 05:35.920
What is it?

05:35.960 --> 05:37.840
Hello?

05:37.880 --> 05:39.080
JUDITH [over phone]:
So you're still

05:39.120 --> 05:40.440
hanging on to Pieter's phone.

05:40.480 --> 05:41.880
GEORGIA:
What the hell?

05:41.920 --> 05:43.480
[mouthing]

05:43.520 --> 05:45.520
JUDITH:
I got the message you left me.

05:45.560 --> 05:48.760
S-Sounds like
you have questions.

05:48.800 --> 05:50.640
Yeah, I do have a question.

05:50.680 --> 05:53.040
I-- How the fuck
are you still alive?

05:53.080 --> 05:55.480
JUDITH:
Well, let's talk in person.

05:55.520 --> 05:58.200
No. N-No, you know,
I've had enough.

05:58.240 --> 05:59.840
I'm going home.

05:59.880 --> 06:03.080
You and Will and the general
can all just rot together.

06:03.120 --> 06:04.920
I, uh...

06:04.960 --> 06:07.640
I met your friend Adidja.

06:09.280 --> 06:13.160
In fact, uh...
she's with me right now.

06:16.440 --> 06:18.560
Tell me where.

06:21.640 --> 06:23.640
[metal clattering]

06:34.720 --> 06:36.720
[knocking on door]

06:42.440 --> 06:43.960
Hiya, sorry to bother.

06:44.000 --> 06:45.800
We haven't met. Owen.

06:45.840 --> 06:48.920
-Hughes.
-Uh... Georgia.

06:48.960 --> 06:50.560
I was wondering
if you'd seen Nigel.

06:50.600 --> 06:52.600
A black and white sheepdog.

06:52.640 --> 06:54.360
She got a-a white patch
on her nose.

06:54.400 --> 06:56.000
"She"?

06:56.040 --> 06:58.320
Yeah. Uh, when we had her,
we-we thought she was a boy,

06:58.360 --> 06:59.960
-so we, we called her Nigel.
-Oh.

07:00.000 --> 07:01.880
By the time she was giving
birth on the kitchen floor,

07:01.920 --> 07:03.760
it was a bit late
to change her name.

07:03.800 --> 07:06.480
Well, um, no.
I'm sorry. I-I haven't seen her.

07:06.520 --> 07:08.160
-Sorry to have bothered you.
-Yeah, no worries.

07:08.200 --> 07:09.720
Sorry.

07:12.000 --> 07:13.400
OWEN [muffled]:
Nigel!

07:15.200 --> 07:16.760
Nigel!

07:18.160 --> 07:19.560
[sighs]

07:23.160 --> 07:24.480
Any suggestions?

07:24.520 --> 07:26.720
Which way to go first?
I mean,

07:26.760 --> 07:28.920
I don't get over this way
much, to be honest.

07:28.960 --> 07:30.720
Um...

07:30.760 --> 07:32.160
Hang on a second.

07:38.960 --> 07:40.960
♪ ♪

07:46.600 --> 07:48.600
[indistinct chatter]

07:51.440 --> 07:53.360
MARTIN: Did I mention
this is a terrible idea?

07:53.400 --> 07:55.560
I don't know what to say.

07:55.600 --> 07:57.920
Adidja needs my help.

08:21.120 --> 08:23.400
Georgia, I'll be here.

08:23.440 --> 08:25.200
For all the good it'll do you.

08:25.240 --> 08:26.520
Thanks.

08:30.920 --> 08:32.920
[children shouting]

08:43.200 --> 08:45.200
♪ ♪

08:58.320 --> 08:59.760
Where is she?

08:59.800 --> 09:04.240
Dispensed with pleasantries
already, have we?

09:04.280 --> 09:07.600
I asked you a question.

09:07.640 --> 09:10.760
Don't worry, she's safe.

09:12.600 --> 09:15.840
First, I'd like to know
where Will is.

09:15.880 --> 09:18.160
I don't know where he is.

09:18.200 --> 09:20.320
I'm just here
to get Adidja back.

09:20.360 --> 09:21.800
How'd you meet?

09:21.840 --> 09:23.160
You and the girl?

09:24.720 --> 09:26.160
Of course.

09:26.200 --> 09:29.040
I can guess.
I've seen too many of them.

09:29.080 --> 09:31.040
Children grown up too fast,

09:31.080 --> 09:33.120
fighting wars they have
no understanding of.

09:33.160 --> 09:35.680
They get this...

09:35.720 --> 09:37.200
this look in their eyes.

09:42.080 --> 09:45.440
You talk an awful lot
for a dead woman.

09:45.480 --> 09:47.360
When you don't know
who's after you,

09:47.400 --> 09:49.360
it's common sense to lie low.

09:49.400 --> 09:51.600
Your husband, of all people...

09:51.640 --> 09:53.400
gave me that idea. [chuckles]

09:53.440 --> 09:57.440
So what, you just walked out
of there, half dead?

09:57.480 --> 09:59.680
General Azikiwe, he ensured

09:59.720 --> 10:02.520
that the doctors
reported me as deceased.

10:03.640 --> 10:05.200
And where is he now?

10:05.240 --> 10:07.520
The general?

10:07.560 --> 10:10.040
I didn't tell him
I was meeting you.

10:10.080 --> 10:11.840
It's best that way.

10:11.880 --> 10:15.040
He can be... unpredictable.

10:15.080 --> 10:18.640
"Unpredictable"?
He's a fucking murderer, Judith.

10:18.680 --> 10:20.160
You're no better.

10:20.200 --> 10:22.120
You knew that plane
was going down.

10:22.160 --> 10:24.000
You bought Will the ticket
to get on the flight.

10:24.040 --> 10:26.520
So you did find him.

10:28.520 --> 10:30.840
He's no threat to you, Judith.

10:30.880 --> 10:33.720
You'll understand if I don't
just take your word for it.

10:34.760 --> 10:36.360
What happened to you?

10:36.400 --> 10:38.960
Did you just--
did you come out to the Congo

10:39.000 --> 10:40.600
to do something good
and then, what?

10:40.640 --> 10:42.040
Something went wrong?

10:42.080 --> 10:44.480
Or have you always been greedy
and ruthless?

10:44.520 --> 10:48.000
I'm transforming
this bloody place.

10:48.040 --> 10:49.800
My charity.

10:49.840 --> 10:53.120
We don't just...
slap on a Band-Aid.

10:53.160 --> 10:56.680
We work to fix the system,
the politicians,

10:56.720 --> 10:58.760
the businessmen;
we're a long-term solution.

10:58.800 --> 11:00.520
Yeah, because you like
to look virtuous,

11:00.560 --> 11:02.360
you like the shine.

11:02.400 --> 11:03.600
Appearance doesn't always

11:03.640 --> 11:05.160
reflect reality,
though, does it?

11:05.200 --> 11:07.480
If I'd said no
to the offer, what,

11:07.520 --> 11:09.760
you think somehow
the coltan trade in the East

11:09.800 --> 11:11.720
would just... dry up?

11:11.760 --> 11:13.560
You can tell yourself
it was for your charity

11:13.600 --> 11:15.200
if it helps you sleep at night.

11:15.240 --> 11:18.240
You were doing a bad thing
for the right reasons.

11:18.280 --> 11:20.240
The truth is,
when Will caught you out,

11:20.280 --> 11:21.800
you sent him to die.

11:21.840 --> 11:25.240
Azikiwe found out
what he'd been up to

11:25.280 --> 11:27.280
and he told me
to get Will on that flight

11:27.320 --> 11:28.760
and that's all I knew.

11:28.800 --> 11:30.120
God, you sound like Will.

11:30.160 --> 11:32.120
"I didn't know."

11:32.160 --> 11:33.760
Well, you didn't ask.

11:33.800 --> 11:35.960
Because it was easier
to pretend.

11:36.000 --> 11:37.960
You think by looking the other
way, pretending bad things

11:38.000 --> 11:40.400
don't happen
somehow makes it okay?

11:40.440 --> 11:42.280
If you stay quiet,
you're as bad as they are.

11:42.320 --> 11:45.040
I don't have to justify
myself to you.

11:45.080 --> 11:48.120
You can go screaming
to the world about me,

11:48.160 --> 11:51.800
about Azikiwe,
but none of it will stick.

11:51.840 --> 11:53.600
You have no proof.

11:53.640 --> 11:55.320
You tell me where to find Will,

11:55.360 --> 11:58.240
and I'll tell you where Adidja
is, and we're done.

11:58.280 --> 12:03.880
You can go back home and you can
get on with your life.

12:26.120 --> 12:28.080
Will lied to me.

12:28.120 --> 12:31.680
He let me believe he was dead.

12:31.720 --> 12:35.480
He found somebody else.
They have a baby.

12:40.960 --> 12:43.240
That must have hurt.

12:43.280 --> 12:45.840
You didn't have
to threaten a child.

12:45.880 --> 12:47.840
I'd have told you
where Will was.

12:47.880 --> 12:50.960
The fucker deserves
everything he gets.

12:52.920 --> 12:55.760
Ah. Rwanda?

12:55.800 --> 12:59.320
-Thank you.
-Where is Adidja?

13:02.040 --> 13:05.000
-You'll find her here.
-Who's holding her?

13:05.040 --> 13:08.640
Despite what you think
about me, Georgia...

13:11.400 --> 13:15.440
...I'm not a monster.

13:15.480 --> 13:19.080
You'll understand if I don't
take your word for it.

13:31.240 --> 13:32.720
[phone ringing]

13:35.040 --> 13:36.600
MARTIN [over phone]:
Georgia.

13:36.640 --> 13:38.200
I'm coming out.
I'll be with you in 30 seconds.

13:38.240 --> 13:40.880
No, don't. Turn round,
go back the other way.

13:40.920 --> 13:44.280
There are two men with guns
watching you. Turn round.

13:44.320 --> 13:46.480
-I see them.
-Go, go.

13:46.520 --> 13:48.560
Turn left
when you get to the end.

14:17.920 --> 14:21.240
[phone ringing]

14:21.280 --> 14:22.560
MARTIN:
I'm heading towards you.

14:22.600 --> 14:24.160
No.

14:24.200 --> 14:26.240
There's got to be a way out
the back of this market.

14:26.280 --> 14:28.040
Meet me there.

14:28.080 --> 14:29.760
Where are you now?

14:29.800 --> 14:33.400
Georgia? Georgia.

14:38.880 --> 14:41.800
Bonjour, madame.
[speaking in French]

15:01.760 --> 15:03.760
[panting]

15:27.080 --> 15:29.360
[man grunting]

15:29.400 --> 15:30.640
[shouting]

15:30.680 --> 15:32.880
[panting]

15:39.200 --> 15:41.200
[tires screech]

15:55.200 --> 15:57.520
MARTIN:
Are you okay?

15:57.560 --> 15:59.360
-Yeah, just about.
-Yeah?

15:59.400 --> 16:01.160
Don't say I told you so.

16:01.200 --> 16:04.960
I wouldn't dream of it.

16:05.000 --> 16:07.720
Well, that was clearly
a successful meeting.

16:07.760 --> 16:09.720
Yeah.

16:09.760 --> 16:11.800
[liquid pouring]

16:11.840 --> 16:13.840
♪ ♪

16:18.960 --> 16:22.240
Pouring drinks for a dead man?

16:24.120 --> 16:27.400
Your mind is rotten.

16:30.080 --> 16:33.160
[laughs softly]

16:33.200 --> 16:34.520
[pounding on door]

16:42.400 --> 16:44.800
[panting]:
You had me followed?

16:44.840 --> 16:47.080
Excuse me?

16:47.120 --> 16:50.600
There's talk about a white girl
being chased in the market.

16:50.640 --> 16:53.720
How did they find her?

16:53.760 --> 16:56.080
'Cause you had your men on me.

16:56.120 --> 16:58.400
You don't fucking trust me.

16:58.440 --> 17:00.000
You seem angry.

17:00.040 --> 17:03.240
Yeah, no shit.

17:03.280 --> 17:07.960
I had someone watch you,
for your own protection.

17:08.000 --> 17:10.360
You're paranoid.
You don't trust anyone.

17:10.400 --> 17:12.160
You wanted to check up on me.

17:12.200 --> 17:15.920
And aren't I fortunate
that I did?

17:15.960 --> 17:18.000
Or were you going to tell me?

17:18.040 --> 17:20.280
I was handling it,
for Christ's sake.

17:20.320 --> 17:25.240
And Georgia,
she has no proof of anything.

17:25.280 --> 17:28.040
She saw me kill a man.

17:28.080 --> 17:30.400
And so did her friend.

17:30.440 --> 17:33.720
And you want her to walk free?

17:33.760 --> 17:36.560
To tell the world?

17:36.600 --> 17:41.320
I want you to trust me.

17:41.360 --> 17:43.200
[scoffs]

17:43.240 --> 17:47.400
To tell me what's in your mind,
because we're in this together.

17:47.440 --> 17:49.440
[laughs]

17:57.960 --> 18:01.200
Is that what you think?

18:02.840 --> 18:05.840
I think I asked you to do a job.

18:05.880 --> 18:09.640
I am the one who makes
the difficult decisions

18:09.680 --> 18:12.080
so you can turn your head.

18:15.400 --> 18:17.360
Yes.

18:17.400 --> 18:21.320
But Georgia told me
where Will is.

18:30.440 --> 18:32.800
Tell me where.

18:41.320 --> 18:44.920
Well, this is the address.

18:44.960 --> 18:47.680
-Are you sure?
-Uh-huh.

18:47.720 --> 18:50.520
It's Avenue de Kabambare, yeah?

18:50.560 --> 18:52.480
Georgia, just a second.

18:52.520 --> 18:54.880
Judith gave us this address.

18:54.920 --> 18:57.080
How do we know it's safe?

18:57.120 --> 19:00.920
We don't,
but I have to go inside.

19:05.400 --> 19:07.400
[car door closes]

19:21.360 --> 19:23.400
[children shouting in distance]

19:47.160 --> 19:49.200
♪ ♪

19:55.400 --> 19:57.400
[metal clanging]

20:01.320 --> 20:03.320
Hi.

20:04.480 --> 20:06.440
Where have you been?

20:06.480 --> 20:09.120
I came back to find you.
There was a woman.

20:09.160 --> 20:10.880
She said you would be here.

20:10.920 --> 20:13.000
I know, she shouldn't have
done that. I'm so sorry.

20:16.120 --> 20:19.600
-This is my home now, isn't it?
-No.

20:19.640 --> 20:22.600
We can find a-a home
that's right for you.

20:22.640 --> 20:25.440
I-I don't know anything
about this place.

20:27.040 --> 20:31.240
But sooner or later,
you'll have to go home.

20:40.760 --> 20:43.080
Oh, what's that?

20:43.120 --> 20:45.160
I wanted to give you something.

20:45.200 --> 20:46.680
It's not much.

20:49.080 --> 20:51.280
No, it's beautiful. I love it.

20:52.280 --> 20:54.320
MARTIN:
Georgia.

21:00.360 --> 21:02.560
♪ ♪

21:09.960 --> 21:12.080
ADIDJA:
Y-You should go.

21:17.600 --> 21:19.560
Good-bye.

21:29.080 --> 21:31.080
[panting]

21:36.640 --> 21:38.720
[metal clanging]

21:56.160 --> 21:58.160
♪ ♪

22:10.680 --> 22:13.840
She'll be okay.

22:13.880 --> 22:16.080
I know.

22:23.680 --> 22:27.200
Nigel! Where the hell are we?

22:27.240 --> 22:29.680
There are some crevices up here
I thought we should check,

22:29.720 --> 22:31.600
in case she's fallen down,

22:31.640 --> 22:34.440
especially with it snowing
up here this morning.

22:34.480 --> 22:39.280
Oh, it's freezing up here,
but she's made it through worse.

22:45.040 --> 22:48.640
-Let's check that cave.
-Yeah, that's where I'm heading.

22:54.560 --> 22:57.960
OWEN:
Nigel!

22:58.000 --> 23:00.000
-GEORGIA: No?
-OWEN: No.

23:02.680 --> 23:04.680
[wind whistling]

23:04.720 --> 23:07.800
[sighs]

23:07.840 --> 23:09.800
So what brings you out
to these parts then?

23:09.840 --> 23:11.000
You don't sound local.

23:11.040 --> 23:13.560
Oh, the cabin was my dad's.

23:13.600 --> 23:15.720
He bought it to be
a-a holiday home,

23:15.760 --> 23:18.680
but he mainly was fixing it up
all the time.

23:18.720 --> 23:20.640
Mr. Wells?

23:20.680 --> 23:25.160
When I was a kid, I got stuck
outside your place in a storm.

23:25.200 --> 23:28.480
This man took us in,
gave us a nice cup of tea.

23:28.520 --> 23:31.440
Mr. Wells, his name was.

23:31.480 --> 23:35.480
Surrounded with wood
and paint and chaos.

23:35.520 --> 23:37.720
[chuckles] That's my dad.

23:37.760 --> 23:41.160
You probably think I'm mad.
All this just for a dog.

23:41.200 --> 23:45.320
No, I don't. I get it.

23:47.280 --> 23:50.760
Anyway, best turn back.
We're gonna lose light soon.

23:50.800 --> 23:52.600
No, we'll be good
for another hour or so.

23:52.640 --> 23:53.760
Sure?

23:53.800 --> 23:57.680
Yeah. I don't like giving up.

24:00.880 --> 24:02.880
[plane passing overhead]

24:05.320 --> 24:07.000
Okay.

24:09.040 --> 24:11.440
Our flight's not for an hour,

24:11.480 --> 24:13.840
so let's find somewhere
to wait, hmm?

24:13.880 --> 24:16.760
But I don't think here
is a good idea.

24:16.800 --> 24:18.360
I think it would be
safer inside.

24:18.400 --> 24:20.400
No, this is, this is
where we came,

24:20.440 --> 24:23.120
me and Pieter and Emmanuel.

24:23.160 --> 24:27.160
Talk about coming
full bloody circle.

24:30.160 --> 24:33.720
All those times I cried for him,
and for what?

24:33.760 --> 24:37.600
Emmanuel's dead
and Pieter's dead,

24:37.640 --> 24:41.000
and Will's off in his
new life in Rwanda.

24:41.040 --> 24:43.280
And all those people
that died on that plane,

24:43.320 --> 24:46.120
just so the general
could carry on getting rich.

24:48.120 --> 24:51.160
It has to mean something,
doesn't it, Martin?

24:51.200 --> 24:54.840
-What do you mean?
-[stammers] Coming out here.

24:54.880 --> 24:57.040
It has to mean something.

25:02.600 --> 25:06.200
All those relatives
of everyone on Flight 19,

25:06.240 --> 25:07.440
they deserve to know
what happened.

25:07.480 --> 25:08.680
Listen, in case
you've forgotten,

25:08.720 --> 25:10.920
someone tried to kill us
not so long ago.

25:10.960 --> 25:12.600
But the man who brought
that plane down

25:12.640 --> 25:14.000
cannot get away with it.

25:14.040 --> 25:15.640
No. So, we go home,

25:15.680 --> 25:18.120
I put you in touch with the
right people to talk to...

25:18.160 --> 25:20.280
But we're here.
We-We-We're here now.

25:20.320 --> 25:22.440
Yes, and what are we
going to do?

25:22.480 --> 25:24.880
I don't know, but I never did
like giving up.

25:24.920 --> 25:27.760
Georgia...

25:32.960 --> 25:34.960
♪ ♪

25:36.320 --> 25:39.160
[knocking on door]

25:41.320 --> 25:42.520
Hi.

25:46.080 --> 25:50.120
So this man, Pieter Bello,

25:50.160 --> 25:52.320
he is who killed my husband?

25:52.360 --> 25:56.760
Yeah. He didn't want us
asking any more questions.

25:56.800 --> 25:58.320
Once I ignored his note

25:58.360 --> 26:01.160
telling me to go home,
we went and found

26:01.200 --> 26:03.240
his ex-wife and his daughter,

26:03.280 --> 26:06.720
and he sent somebody
to deal with us.

26:06.760 --> 26:10.960
And Pieter Bello,
where is he now?

26:11.000 --> 26:13.960
He's dead.

26:16.360 --> 26:18.560
[sighs] It's a lot.
I know it's a lot,

26:18.600 --> 26:21.000
but if you look
in Gaelle's diary,

26:21.040 --> 26:24.200
you'll see she was asked to
carry something onto that plane.

26:24.240 --> 26:25.880
It was a bomb.

26:25.920 --> 26:28.800
The people on that plane
were murdered.

26:30.480 --> 26:32.080
Ivette, I promised you

26:32.120 --> 26:34.640
that I would find out who killed
your husband, and I have,

26:34.680 --> 26:36.880
but it means nothing
if the people responsible

26:36.920 --> 26:38.440
aren't held accountable
for what they did.

26:38.480 --> 26:41.840
Oh, oh, oh, you-you don't
understand, do you?

26:41.880 --> 26:45.800
This is Congo.

26:45.840 --> 26:48.120
The snakes in
our government bite

26:48.160 --> 26:50.160
and then slither
back into the grass.

26:50.200 --> 26:52.760
This country is broken,

26:52.800 --> 26:55.520
and there isn't
any way to fix it.

26:55.560 --> 26:57.160
It's a bucket with a hole in it.

26:57.200 --> 26:59.840
Why you keep trying
to fill it with water?

26:59.880 --> 27:03.680
Ivette, are you in touch
with any other relatives

27:03.720 --> 27:05.680
who had loved ones
on Sankuru 19?

27:05.720 --> 27:07.360
I am.

27:07.400 --> 27:09.960
Emmanuel used to talk
with the relatives

27:10.000 --> 27:11.880
through a phone group.

27:11.920 --> 27:14.000
I started using it when he died.

27:14.040 --> 27:16.400
We talk sometimes.

27:16.440 --> 27:18.520
GEORGIA:
Can I send a message?

27:21.160 --> 27:23.280
What is it you want?

27:23.320 --> 27:25.280
-We need to get them a message.
-Why?

27:25.320 --> 27:27.680
Because it's time this changed.

27:32.360 --> 27:35.040
[mutters quietly]

27:35.080 --> 27:38.120
[Ivette sighs]

27:50.520 --> 27:52.960
[door closes]

27:58.840 --> 28:00.200
STEFANIA:
Perhaps it's someone else

28:00.240 --> 28:02.400
come to stab you in the back.

28:02.440 --> 28:06.920
Makes you wonder how
you will ever sleep again,

28:06.960 --> 28:09.560
doesn't it?

28:16.240 --> 28:19.000
Who's that?

28:19.040 --> 28:21.400
Sir. You wanted
to be informed...

28:22.840 --> 28:24.280
It's happening?

28:24.320 --> 28:26.120
We have two men in Ruhengeri.

28:26.160 --> 28:29.400
They're on their way to Will
Mason's house at this moment.

28:29.440 --> 28:31.240
And if they're found...?

28:31.280 --> 28:34.160
There's nothing that will link
them to us. They're freelancers.

28:34.200 --> 28:36.440
Perfect.

28:39.240 --> 28:42.440
Last thing I need is to start
another damn war.

28:43.880 --> 28:45.880
♪ ♪

28:59.720 --> 29:01.840
Shh...

29:29.000 --> 29:30.960
-[baby fusses]
-Shh...

29:31.000 --> 29:34.080
-[knocking on door]
-[shushing]

29:46.600 --> 29:48.280
THIERRY:
Will Mason.

29:48.320 --> 29:50.640
This is for you.

29:50.680 --> 29:53.240
-Will Mason.
-[both speaking Kinyarwandan]

29:53.280 --> 29:54.440
[screams]

29:54.480 --> 29:57.480
[muffled screaming]

30:10.800 --> 30:12.160
[speaking Kinyarwandan]

30:23.560 --> 30:26.880
Shh...

30:26.920 --> 30:30.320
[phone ringing]

30:30.360 --> 30:31.920
JUDITH [on recording]:
This is Judith Gray.

30:31.960 --> 30:34.360
Please leave a message.

30:34.400 --> 30:36.800
GEORGIA: I'm still alive,
and I'm still here.

30:36.840 --> 30:40.520
If you want to know why,
go to Azikiwe's house now.

30:50.440 --> 30:52.480
You ready for this?

31:12.840 --> 31:16.040
Well, seems like faith
is what people need.

31:16.080 --> 31:18.080
[crowd chanting]

31:27.920 --> 31:29.840
I didn't know if you'd come.

31:29.880 --> 31:32.960
Sometimes we must keep filling
the bucket with water, yes?

31:52.920 --> 31:54.920
[chanting continues]

32:15.280 --> 32:17.280
[phone ringing]

32:21.960 --> 32:23.760
GEORGIA [over phone]:
These are the family and friends

32:23.800 --> 32:24.960
of the people who died

32:25.000 --> 32:27.160
on Sankuru Flight 19.

32:27.200 --> 32:28.880
Innocent people who were
sent to their deaths.

32:28.920 --> 32:31.520
I'm meant to what,

32:31.560 --> 32:35.520
throw my hands up now, huh?

32:35.560 --> 32:37.520
Meant to come out,

32:37.560 --> 32:39.360
repent my sins?

32:39.400 --> 32:40.960
AZIKIWE:
Tell her to go to hell.

32:51.120 --> 32:53.120
[chanting continues]

33:05.160 --> 33:07.400
All of these people,

33:07.440 --> 33:09.560
they've lost people they love
because of a bloody rock

33:09.600 --> 33:12.560
that's been dug out of the mud
and fought over, died over,

33:12.600 --> 33:15.400
just so that we can
hunch over our phones.

33:15.440 --> 33:19.080
Sad, you know.

33:19.120 --> 33:22.800
You're exploiting
these poor people's grief

33:22.840 --> 33:25.000
all because you're bitter
that your husband

33:25.040 --> 33:27.440
didn't fucking love you.

33:27.480 --> 33:30.640
It's not about Will
anymore, Judith.

33:30.680 --> 33:32.640
Sure.

33:32.680 --> 33:35.440
Go home, Georgia.

33:35.480 --> 33:38.840
There was a full inquiry
into the crash, remember?

33:38.880 --> 33:41.680
It was an accident.

33:41.720 --> 33:46.880
What you're doing isn't gonna
change anybody's mind.

33:46.920 --> 33:48.600
That's where you're wrong.

33:48.640 --> 33:50.640
[chanting continues]

34:11.600 --> 34:13.600
[phone ringing]

34:16.280 --> 34:18.320
[chanting over phone]

34:31.440 --> 34:33.400
GEORGIA [over phone]:
Honesty.

34:33.440 --> 34:37.160
For once in your life,
that's what I'm asking.

34:37.200 --> 34:39.960
If you owe me anything,
it's this.

34:40.000 --> 34:42.200
Tell the truth.

34:55.280 --> 34:59.240
OWEN: You, uh, don't mind
if I use your loo, do you?

34:59.280 --> 35:02.480
GEORGIA:
Uh, sure.

35:04.480 --> 35:06.600
It's just through there.

35:06.640 --> 35:08.640
-Thanks.
-Yeah.

35:11.600 --> 35:14.040
I suppose she'll turn up
in the morning.

35:16.080 --> 35:18.640
What? What is it?

35:18.680 --> 35:22.920
You know, I probably should have
told you this before, but, um,

35:22.960 --> 35:25.640
it's not the first time
she's done it.

35:25.680 --> 35:28.080
She runs away
most days, actually.

35:28.120 --> 35:30.440
Sometimes don't see her
for a few days.

35:30.480 --> 35:32.920
So why have you had me...?

35:32.960 --> 35:35.400
Look, I just wanted
to get to know you.

35:35.440 --> 35:39.600
We haven't met,
but I've seen you here.

35:39.640 --> 35:43.200
Beautiful girl shouldn't
be out here on her own.

35:44.880 --> 35:46.880
You say she does this a lot?

35:46.920 --> 35:48.720
Yeah. A few times, now.

35:48.760 --> 35:52.320
Animals, eh?
They do what they do.

35:52.360 --> 35:54.320
Ever thought maybe it's you?

35:54.360 --> 35:56.080
Maybe she wants
to be somewhere else,

35:56.120 --> 35:58.160
and you should just let her go.

35:59.640 --> 36:01.640
You can leave now.

36:05.080 --> 36:07.480
Fine.

36:09.960 --> 36:14.800
You know, it's no surprise to me
you ended up out here...

36:14.840 --> 36:16.800
[laughs softly]

36:16.840 --> 36:18.760
...all on your own.

36:18.800 --> 36:23.000
You've got no idea how or why
I ended up here,

36:23.040 --> 36:24.400
and what I've seen.

36:24.440 --> 36:26.000
You wouldn't believe me anyway.

36:26.040 --> 36:28.120
Just go and piss off now.

36:28.160 --> 36:30.160
[laughs softly]

37:00.120 --> 37:02.120
♪ ♪

37:16.840 --> 37:18.840
[birds chirping]

37:24.360 --> 37:26.360
[knocking on door]

37:31.080 --> 37:33.360
Hey.

37:33.400 --> 37:35.840
Hello.

37:38.200 --> 37:40.760
WILL: I didn't know,
but I didn't say anything.

37:40.800 --> 37:46.080
This shows the money,
and where it was going.

37:48.080 --> 37:53.640
I have e-mails and texts,

37:53.680 --> 37:58.200
that help confirm
what I'm saying.

37:58.240 --> 38:00.200
[exhales]

38:25.640 --> 38:28.200
Why are you telling
all of this now?

38:28.240 --> 38:30.640
After all this time?

38:30.680 --> 38:32.840
[stammers]

38:32.880 --> 38:35.440
I've seen what
it does to people,

38:35.480 --> 38:38.840
losing someone.

38:38.880 --> 38:42.400
And it's happened
to too many people.

38:42.440 --> 38:44.800
[door opens]

39:04.040 --> 39:08.000
What will happen to him now,
I wonder?

39:08.040 --> 39:11.560
He'll try and strike
a deal, probably.

39:11.600 --> 39:13.520
Bloody cockroach.

39:13.560 --> 39:16.440
Oh, as long as he does what
he came to do, I don't care.

39:16.480 --> 39:20.120
-[door closes]
-He's not my problem anymore.

39:24.320 --> 39:28.960
AZIKIWE: My uncle told me a story once when I was young.

39:29.000 --> 39:30.320
The story he told me

39:30.360 --> 39:33.360
was about a farmer's donkey.

39:33.400 --> 39:38.080
This donkey fell down
a deep well.

39:38.120 --> 39:40.280
The donkey sat at the bottom
of the well

39:40.320 --> 39:43.720
squealing and crying for hours.

39:43.760 --> 39:46.360
The farmer looked down at him,
and he decided

39:46.400 --> 39:48.960
that the animal was old,

39:49.000 --> 39:53.200
and that he needed
to cover the well, anyway.

39:53.240 --> 39:56.920
Well, they began to shovel dirt
down into the well,

39:56.960 --> 39:58.520
onto the donkey.

39:58.560 --> 40:00.120
More and more dirt.

40:00.160 --> 40:02.360
But then he stopped.

40:04.560 --> 40:07.520
After shoveling some more dirt,

40:07.560 --> 40:11.680
he'd looked down
to see something amazing.

40:11.720 --> 40:14.680
All the dirt they had thrown
upon the creature's back

40:14.720 --> 40:20.120
had fallen to the side
when he shook it off his back.

40:20.160 --> 40:25.360
Slowly but surely,
the dirt began to build,

40:25.400 --> 40:31.000
until the donkey
got higher and higher,

40:31.040 --> 40:35.320
until eventually,
he could walk out of that well.

40:35.360 --> 40:37.360
[laughs softly]

40:39.440 --> 40:41.440
[moans]

40:44.240 --> 40:45.600
ARIEL:
And why did your uncle

40:45.640 --> 40:47.640
tell you this story?

40:50.840 --> 40:54.640
To make me feel better.

40:57.080 --> 40:59.080
[crying]

41:07.680 --> 41:11.560
The donkey could leave that well

41:11.600 --> 41:15.920
so it could once more
carry a load on its back.

41:17.960 --> 41:23.560
Free, so it could be
a slave once more.

41:29.640 --> 41:33.440
But I am no slave.

41:38.520 --> 41:40.520
[gun drops]

41:47.280 --> 41:49.280
[sirens wailing]

41:55.840 --> 41:57.480
[tires screeching]

42:01.720 --> 42:04.800
Let go.

42:04.840 --> 42:07.720
-[crutch clatters]
-[grunts]

42:07.760 --> 42:09.640
[shouts]

42:23.000 --> 42:25.000
[sirens wailing]

42:39.440 --> 42:41.680
Okay?

42:41.720 --> 42:43.680
Yeah.

42:47.280 --> 42:49.000
[quietly]:
Come on.

43:00.360 --> 43:01.760
[engine starts]

43:16.920 --> 43:18.720
[grunts]

43:18.760 --> 43:22.200
Well, that was fun.
[chuckles]

43:22.240 --> 43:24.800
Strewth. What did you get for it
in the end?

43:24.840 --> 43:28.000
Don't ask. It's not exactly
prime real estate, is it?

43:28.040 --> 43:30.720
I don't know. You might be half
a dozen sheep better off.

43:30.760 --> 43:32.760
[laughs softly]

43:35.280 --> 43:36.400
[chuckles]

43:36.440 --> 43:40.080
She was fast asleep just now.

43:47.160 --> 43:49.560
Oh.

43:49.600 --> 43:51.720
[sniffles]

43:51.760 --> 43:56.160
I guess I'll start
loading the stuff.

43:56.200 --> 43:58.360
Thank you.

43:58.400 --> 44:00.120
You don't have to thank me.

44:00.160 --> 44:02.920
I do. You are giving me a home.

44:02.960 --> 44:04.920
You have a home.

44:04.960 --> 44:08.360
We're just making
a new one together. Okay?

44:11.920 --> 44:13.080
Come on.

44:13.120 --> 44:16.640
Should we give him a hand?

44:16.680 --> 44:18.640
-Watch out.
-[Martin grunts]

44:18.680 --> 44:20.760
Is this the well-practiced art

44:20.800 --> 44:22.240
of getting out of
carrying stuff?

44:22.280 --> 44:24.240
No, no, no. No.
We're gonna do it.

44:24.280 --> 44:26.640
[laughs]

44:37.720 --> 44:38.960
MARTIN
Look at that.

44:40.960 --> 44:43.920
Look. Look at that dog.

44:43.960 --> 44:46.160
There's no one around for miles.

44:46.200 --> 44:49.240
I think he's lost.

44:49.280 --> 44:51.240
No, she's not lost.

44:51.280 --> 44:53.960
MARTIN:
You sure?

44:54.000 --> 44:57.080
Yeah. Come on. Let's get going.

44:57.120 --> 44:58.320
Okay.

45:22.360 --> 45:24.360
♪ ♪
